For picking sector types (hostile, friendly, nebula):

* 20% chance of nebula, otherwise:
* An independent 60% chance of being friendly, 40% hostile

This is handled in StarMap::GetRandomSectorChoice, where:
0=friendly
1=hostile
2=nebula

And >2 seems to involve a grey dot on the sector map, which
might be somehow related to the crystal homeworlds? Or maybe
just something cut (this can be seen in RenderSectorMap).


StarMap::GenerateSectorMap:

This is responsible for generating the map of all the different
sectors. It sets up the first and last sectors, and calls
AddSectorColumn six times to fill in the middle.


StarMap::AddSectorColumn:

This is the core of FTL's sector map generation. It builds a column
of sectors, as seen on the map.

It picks a random number between 2 and 4 inclusive, which
is the number of sectors in this column. It always picks
a different number (via re-rolling) than the last column.

The exception is the first column, which always has two
sectors, presumably to avoid giving the player more than two options.

For each column, consider the number of sectors in the previous
column to figure out how to link them up:

4 prev, 2 now: 1st sector links to previous 1st/2nd, 2nd links to 3rd/4th
2 prev, 4 now: 1st and 2nd links to previous 1st, 3rd and 4th link to previous 2nd

Any other case (1 prev, 2 now for the first sector, or between 2/3, 4/3, 3/4, 3/2)
is handled as follows:

For each new sector:
 * Find it's 'peer', the sector with the corresponding index in
   the previous column.
 * Connect the peer to the previously-added new sector, or do nothing
   if we're adding the first sector in the column.
 * Create the new sector, linking it with it's peer
 * If this column has more sectors than the last column, add a new
   column in the 2nd position to keep the connections right.

The actual implementation is annoying to read due to inlining, but searching
for 'FTL sector map' in your favourite search engine should make it obvious
what's happening here - link up all the sectors without any of the neighbour
links overlapping.
